g, Stuttgart, Germany":"Stuttgart, Baden-Württemberg, Germany","Wasserbourg,,Baden Württemberg,Germany":"Baden-Württemberg, Germany","nameMeanings":[{"name":"von","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of Welsh   Vaughan  .","Chinese: variant of   Wong  .","Cambodian: written វ៉ុន, unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Vaughan","meanings":["Welsh: from <i>fychan</i>, a lenited form of <i>bychan</i>, a diminutive of <i>bach</i> ‘little’. This was often used to distinguish the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, typically the son of a father with the same name."]}]},{"name":"Margareta","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margaret","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]},{"name":"Margarete","meanings":["from Greek.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margrethe","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]},{"name":"Margaretha","meanings":["from Greek.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margareta von Müllenark was born in 1080, in Flinsbach, St. Pölten Land, Lower Austria, Austria as the daughter of Gerhard von Müllenark and Regelinde. She married Engelbert von Schwarzenburg about 1100. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. She died on 17 July 1112, at the age of 32."},"et":{"1080–17 juillet 1112":"1080–17. juuli 1112","1080–1112":"1080–1112","1085–1125":"1085–1125","1097–1134":"1097–1134","1102–1179":"1102–1179","1045–1114":"1045–1114","–Female":"Surnud","1080":"1080","1097":"1097","1085":"1085","ABT 1097":"umbes 1097","1114":"1114","1125":"1125","ABT 1100":"umbes 1100","1179":"1179","1102":"1102","1134":"1134","1112":"1112","ABT 1102":"umbes 1102","17 juillet 1112":"17. juuli 1112","1045":"1045","Flinsbach":"Flinsbach, St. Pölten Land, Niederösterreich, Austria","Schwarzenberg, Kressberg, Stuttgart, Germany":"Stuttg